caption: Tonight was one of those nights... Everyone's cranky and hungry. My lessons ran late. Mom didn't feel like cooking, much less cooking and then begging and pleading with people to eat it. So a couple boxes of Pasta Roni, canned green beans, and pigs in a blanket made from canned biscuits was all I could muster. Yes, I realize how processed it is. No, I'm not trying to kill my kids. Judge if you must. 😉 When Mr. Saves (who happens to LOVE Pasta Roni 😂) walked through the door he commented on how it's been YEARS since I've made it for him. I then made some snarky comment about it being "years since we were Pasta Roni poor" which my children overheard. My very curious and very smart seven year old started in on the questions. "How poor were we?"... "What does Pasta Roni cost?"... "Are we poor now?"... "How much money does Dad make in a day?"... "Why does Mom work too?"... On and on. I immediately regretted my choice of words.
You see, I vividly remember trying to apply for FAFSA in high school to try and get financial aide for college (a homework assignment for my college prep class) and asking my dad how much money he made so I could fill out the application. His only response was "enough". He wouldn't say anything further. To this day, I have no idea what he makes. NO ONE DOES! And I see now what he was trying to teach me. Self reliance, self worth outside of a salary, the truth that "poor" is a state of mind and that what's on your dinner table or in your bank account doesn't make you "poor". Disclaimer: I'm not delusional enough to think that money problems don't exist. I've lived it. And I in no way, suggest that help shouldn't be taken when necessary (like the FAFSA). BUT what I am saying and what I back peddled to teach my children tonight is this... Money won't ever make you happy. It won't ever define how much you're worth or what you're capable of. And it should NEVER replace the things that make life worth living. Things like sitting around a table with a healthy beautiful family in a tiny warm apartment eating Pasta Roni. Those people weren't poor. They were simply working their way through some things. Those people had ALL of the most important things.
